related_questions.question: How much of the world's power is solar?
related_questions.snippet: Solar generation is projected to climb from 7 percent of total U.S. renewable generation in 2015 to about 36 percent by 2050, making it the fastest-growing electricity source. Globally, renewables made up 24 percent of electricity generation in 2014, much of it from hydropower (17 percent).

related_questions.question: How much solar capacity and generation do we have?
related_questions.snippet: As of the end of 2017, the United States had over 50 gigawatts (GW) of installed photovoltaic capacity. In the twelve months through December 2018, utility scale solar power generated 66.6 terawatt-hours (TWh), 1.66% of total U.S. electricity.

related_questions.snippet: There are now 1.3 million solar installations across the United States, with a cumulative capacity of over 40 gigawatts.
